SIMPLE: remember
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Remember
<hw>Re*mem"ber</hw> <pr>(r?-m?m"b?r)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Remembered</conjf>
<pr>(-b?rd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Remembering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OF. <ets>remebrer</ets>, L.
<ets>rememorari</ets>; pref. <ets>re-</ets> re- + <ets>memorare</ets> to
bring to remembrance, from <ets>memor</ets> mindful. See
<er>Memory</er>, and cf. <er>Rememorate</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
have (a notion or idea) come into the mind again, as previously
perceived, known, or felt; to have a renewed apprehension of; to bring
to mind again; to think of again; to recollect; <as>as, I
<ex>remember</ex> the fact; he <ex>remembers</ex> the events of his
childhood; I cannot <ex>remember</ex> dates.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We are said to <qex>remember</qex> anything, when the idea of it
arises in the mind with the consciousness that we have had this idea
before.</q> <rj><qau>I. Watts.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To be capable of recalling when required; to keep in
mind; to be continually aware or thoughtful of; to preserve fresh in the
memory; to attend to; to think of with gratitude, affection, respect, or
any other emotion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Remember</qex> the Sabbath day, to keep it holy.</q>
<rj><qau>Ex. xx. 8.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That they may have their wages duly paid 'em,⟦br⟧
And something over to <qex>remember</qex> me by.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Remember</qex> what I warn thee; shun to taste.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1216 --></p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To put in mind; to remind; -- also used reflexively
and impersonally.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Remembering</xex> them the trith of what they themselves
known.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My friends <qex>remembered</qex> me of home.</q>
<rj><qau>Chapman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Remember</qex> you of passed heaviness.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And well thou wost [knowest] if it <qex>remember</qex> thee.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To mention.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧As in
many cases hereafter to be <xex>remembered</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Ayliffe.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To recall to the mind of another, as in the friendly
messages, <xex>remember</xex> me to him, he wishes to be
<xex>remembered</xex> to you, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Remember</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Remember
<hw>Re*mem"ber</hw> <pr>(r?-m?m"b?r)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To
execise or have the power of memory; <as>as, some <ex>remember</ex>
better than others</as>.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rememberable</ent>⟦br⟧
